  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: Long Coat, or the Sensible Puppy Cut" imageAlt="Shih Tzu puppy having its long coat brushed and face tidied" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>Left long, the Shih Tzu coat is a genuine commitment: daily brushing to the skin, a topknot to keep hair out of the eyes, and mats forming anywhere you skip. Almost every Singapore Shih Tzu lives in a puppy cut instead, and we recommend it without hesitation: brush 2 to 3 times a week, salon groom every 4 to 6 weeks, and everyone's happier, the dog included, in our humidity.</p>
      <p>The daily non-negotiable is the face: those large eyes and facial folds need a quick wipe each day to prevent tear staining and skin irritation. The wipes are in your starter kit, and it takes ten seconds once it's habit.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Shih Tzu Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Shih Tzu puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Shih Tzu goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The Shih Tzu health points worth knowing: the short muzzle means brachycephalic airway traits, so snoring is normal but laboured breathing after mild activity is a vet visit; the large, prominent eyes scratch more easily than most breeds', so anything weepy or squinty gets checked early; patellar luxation, the small-breed kneecap issue; and dental crowding in the short jaw, which the day-one oral care routine manages.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. For portioning guidance see the <a href="/learn/puppy-health" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <div class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Living Flat-Faced in Singapore: The Heat Rules" imagePosition="none" variant="card">
      <p>The Shih Tzu's short muzzle is part of its charm and its one genuine vulnerability here. Dogs cool themselves by panting, and a flat-faced breed pants less efficiently, which in a climate that sits at 32°C by 11am means the heat rules are not optional: walk before 9am or after 6pm, never at midday; shade and water on every outing; and home means a ventilated, fan-cooled or air-conditioned room, not an enclosed balcony.</p>
      <p>Follow those rules and the breed thrives here, as it has for generations of Singapore families. The signs to act on immediately: heavy relentless panting, a tongue gone very dark red, wobbliness. Cool water on the body, aircon, and the vet, in that order.</p>
      <div slot="side" class="clay h-full bg-[var(--color-peach-100)] p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs font-bold uppercase text-[var(--color-cream-500)]" style="letter-spacing: 0.08em;">The heat rules</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3">
          {[
            'Walks before 9am or after 6pm only',
            'Cool, ventilated room during the day',
            'Water available everywhere, always',
          ].map((fact) => (
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-cream-700)]">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" class="mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-[var(--color-coral-500)]" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M20 6 9 17l-5-5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" />
              </svg>
              {fact}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </CaptionedBlock>

    <PawTrail bg="bg-[var(--color-surface)]" colorClass="text-[var(--color-coral-300)]" />
  </div>

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Shih Tzu's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Shih Tzu puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Shih Tzu explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about <a href="/delivery" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm, cool and predictable. A fixed feeding routine, the toilet pads where we placed them, and the daily face-wipe habit starting immediately. Some night whimpering is normal adjustment.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer this week; the Shih Tzu's gentle stubborn streak is easiest to shape early. See <a href="/free-training" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>. For anything in between, you WhatsApp us.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

